# Dell XC730xd-12 profile.
#
# XC = Dell's Nutanix OEM rebadge of the R730xd. Same chassis, same
# 60mm hot-swap fans, same iDRAC8 BMC behavior. Use R730xd-equivalent
# tuning (MIN_FAN=10 — BMC clamps lower values to a safety RPM, no
# fan-stall risk).
#
# product_name "Dell XC730xd-12" → detect_model output "dell_xc730xd_12"
# (the current detection doesn't strip the "Dell " prefix; this file
# matches what's actually produced).

# Primary NAS — drive longevity prioritized over noise (operator: safe > quiet).
#
# Measured on this box (2026-06): the 12-bay cage + 60mm fans give this array a
# ~4.5 min thermal dead time with its time constant about equal to it, and a
# natural min-fan rest of ~45-46°C. On that plant you can have cool+stable or
# cool+quiet, not both — servoing a fan curve down to a cool target hunts or
# overshoots (see git history v0.3.14→v0.3.16). So instead of chasing a target
# with the PID, we hold a high CONSTANT chassis floor: enough steady airflow to
# park every drive in the ~38°C ideal-longevity band with ZERO servoing — no
# hunt, no overshoot, rock-stable and cool.
#
# Measured fan→temp on this array: ~45%→~40°C, ~55%→~38°C. MIN_FAN=55 targets
# the ideal band. The per-class PID + proximity floor still stack ON TOP for
# transients and the emergency trip is unchanged — this only raises the floor
# they can't go below. Noise is intentionally traded for cooler drives.
#
# (HDD_TARGET/HDD_DEADBAND left at the shipped defaults 40/3 — with the floor
# holding drives ~38°C the servo rarely engages; it's just a safety backstop.)
: "${MIN_FAN:=55}"             # constant chassis floor — holds drives ~38°C

# IPMI temperature sensors on the XC730xd-12's iDRAC8. Identical
# layout to r730xd / r730 (same BMC firmware family). Two CPU sensors
# share the name "Temp", distinguished by FreeIPMI record id 26/27.
# Inlet and Exhaust have unique names.
: "${SENSOR_CPU1_NAME:=Temp}"
: "${SENSOR_CPU1_ID:=26}"
: "${SENSOR_CPU2_NAME:=Temp}"
: "${SENSOR_CPU2_ID:=27}"
: "${SENSOR_INLET_NAME:=Inlet Temp}"
: "${SENSOR_EXHAUST_NAME:=Exhaust Temp}"
